<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C21.S4.p1.s1">
Figure 21.4.1 provides surfaces of the scaled Riemann theta function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C21.S4.p1.m1">\hat{\theta}\left(\mathbf{z}\middle|\boldsymbol{{\Omega}}\right)</Math> , with <Math equation-number="21.4.1" mode="display" xml:id="C21.S4.E1">\boldsymbol{{\Omega}}=\begin{bmatrix}1.69098\;3006+0.95105\;6516\,i&amp;1.5+0.3632 7\;1264\,i\\ 1.5+0.36327\;1264\,i&amp;1.30901\;6994+0.95105\;6516\,i\end{bmatrix}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C21.S4.p1.s2">
This Riemann matrix originates from the Riemann surface represented by the algebraic curve <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C21.S4.p1.m2">\mu^{3}-\lambda^{7}+2\lambda^{3}\mu=0</Math> ; compare §21.7(i).
</sentence>

</para>
         

